questions.answer:
**Lock-free:** At least one thread is guaranteed to make progress in a finite number of steps. Other threads may be delayed but the system as a whole never deadlocks or livelocks.

**Wait-free:** Every thread is guaranteed to complete its operation in a bounded number of steps, regardless of what other threads are doing. Stronger guarantee than lock-free.

**Comparison:**
| Property | Mutex-based | Lock-free | Wait-free |
|----------|-------------|-----------|----------|
| Deadlock possible | Yes | No | No |
| Starvation possible | Yes | Yes | No |
| Priority inversion | Yes | No | No |
| ISR-safe | No | Usually | Yes |
| Complexity | Low | Medium | High |

**Lock-free example — SPSC ring buffer:**
```c
// Single-producer single-consumer ring buffer
// Producer only writes head, consumer only writes tail
// Both read the other's index — no locks needed
bool ring_put(Ring *r, uint8_t val) {
    uint32_t next = (r->head + 1) % r->size;
    if (next == r->tail) return false; // Full
    r->buffer[r->head] = val;
    __atomic_store_n(&r->head, next, __ATOMIC_RELEASE);
    return true;
}
```

**Wait-free example — shared flag:**
```c
// ISR sets flag, main loop reads and clears it
// Both complete in O(1) regardless of the other
volatile bool flag = false;
// ISR: flag = true;   (one store — wait-free)
// Main: if (flag) { flag = false; process(); }  (wait-free)
```

**When to use in firmware:**
- **ISR ↔ task communication:** ISRs can't block, so lock-free is mandatory
- **Multi-core MCUs** (Cortex-A, RP2040 dual-core): lock-free queues between cores
- **Safety-critical:** Bounded execution time is provable (WCET analysis)

**When NOT to use:** Complex multi-producer multi-consumer scenarios. The complexity of correct lock-free MPMC structures is enormous — use a mutex unless you have a specific need.

```c
#define DEBOUNCE_MS 50

static volatile uint32_t last_press_time = 0;
static volatile bool button_pressed = false;

void GPIO_Button_ISR(void) {
    uint32_t now = get_tick_ms();
    if ((now - last_press_time) > DEBOUNCE_MS) {
        button_pressed = true;
        last_press_time = now;
    }
    clear_interrupt_flag();
}
```

**Two main approaches:**
1. **ISR + timestamp** (above): Ignore interrupts within debounce window. Simple, low overhead.
2. **Polling + integrator**: Sample button state periodically (1ms timer). Count consecutive same-state samples. Change state after N consistent samples.

The polling approach is more robust for noisy environments and doesn't waste ISR time on bounces.

